top.value: Centenary Action Group has called on the UK government to deliver real change for womens lives in the UK and around the world. Specifically: To implement Section 106 of the Equality Act 2010, requiring political parties to publish their candidate diversity data, and create positive pressure for change; To end harassment in the workplace through introducing a mandatory preventative duty on employers, reinstating third party harassment laws, and championing a progressive ILO Convention at the global level.
The Live Well Social Enterprises programme is working to increase access to affordable healthcare, supports livelihoods and stimulates economic development in communities in Zambia.

The main goal of CARE's response is to sucessfuly contribute to the EBOLA EPR Plan Gola: To reduce the incidence and mortality due to Ebola Virus.Our specific Objective is to increase Community awareness on Ebola prevention

Aligned with Sustainable Development Goals 1, 2, 5 and 13, this project will contribute to the creation of equitable, climate-resilient farming communities where women are empowered, natural resources are sustainably managed

CARE,  and its partners  Plan  will respond to Typhoon Kammuri affected areas in Northern Samar in Philippines to help reach the Typhoon affected beneficiaries under the category of WASH and PROTECTION.

CARE and its partner will respond to the WASH emergency needs of refugees in Bardarash and Gawilan to mitigate health risks associated with inadequate access to water, sanitation and hygiene practices.

CARE aims to to meet the life-saving WASH and temporary shelter needs of the most vulnerable population, especially women and girls, affected by monsoon flooding in NRS by improving water and sanitation access and temporary shelter for 5,080 HH without access to clean water in Buthiduang and housing damages.

Care International proposes to target 1,600 of the most affected and vulnerable households with Vouchers for NFI and Shelter Materials, to allow them to repair their damaged or destroyed housing, and to replace key NFIs lost or damaged in the floods

CARE intervention will support 1,300 vulnerable IDPs households (about 7,800 persons) via cash distribution to cover immediate food needs in complement of dry food already distributed by WFP operations. In addition, CARE raising awareness sessions will benefit not only to IDPs but also host-families in both Districts, this will allow them to increase their knowledge towards gender issues such as gender based violence, nutrition and health practices but also contribute to reduce the risk of tension between both communities.

CARE India will carry out relief distribution (Shelter NFI*; WASH NFI and other Households items**) in Kumartchi block in Cuddalore district. This block is one among the six severely affected. Kumartchi also has more than 70% of Dalit population: this community has emerged as one of the most affected and vulnerable communities in the assessements conducted by the TN IAG, in which CARE also participated.
